      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for this COU.",
      "rationale": "The FEA software (Ansys Mechanical 2021 R2) is used under a validated installation with documented version control, regression test suite, and ISO 9001-compliant QMS at each participating organization. All simulation scripts are stored in a version-controlled repository with peer-review gates. Required level 2 is met; achieved level 3 reflects additional inter-laboratory cross-checks."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed via comparison against NAFEMS benchmark problems LE1 and LE10 for linear elasticity, and against analytical Euler-Bernoulli beam solutions for bending. Results agreed to within 0.3% across all benchmark cases, confirming correct implementation of the governing equations in the solver."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted with four mesh densities (coarse, medium, fine, very fine). Richardson extrapolation was applied to stiffness and peak force QoIs. The grid convergence index (GCI) for the fine mesh was below 1.2% for all QoIs, and the asymptotic ratio confirmed convergence in the monotonic regime. The production mesh corresponds to the fine level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Default solver tolerances (residual < 1e-6) were verified to be sufficient by halving tolerances and confirming QoI changes below 0.1%. Iterative convergence was monitored for all nonlinear load steps; no divergence events were recorded across the 11-construct ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Simulation execution was performed by two independent analysts following a documented simulation protocol. Results were cross-checked between analysts; discrepancies exceeding 0.5% triggered a mandatory review. No unresolved discrepancies were identified. The protocol is stored in the project quality record system."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "A linear-elastic constitutive model with isotropic titanium alloy properties (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) was selected based on the pre-yield loading regime targeted by ASTM F1717. The model form is consistent with published literature for metallic spinal implant FEA. Sensitivity analyses confirmed that plasticity effects are negligible below the yield force QoI."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties were sourced from coupon tensile tests on the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used for the implants (n=5 coupons per lot). Geometric inputs were derived from CMM measurements of each of the 11 constructs, with dimensional uncertainty propagated through the model. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry as measured by the testing laboratories."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested, spanning two independent laboratories (n=6 Lab A, n=5 Lab B). All constructs were manufactured from the same production lot. Sample size is consistent with ASTM F1717 requirements and supports inter-laboratory variability characterization."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single standardized ASTM F1717 condition (static compression-bending, room temperature, displacement rate 25 mm/min). Only one load configuration was evaluated; dynamic or fatigue conditions were not included. This limits the achieved level to 1, below the required level of 2. This shortfall is noted as an accepted limitation given the COU scope."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "A formal parameter equivalency table maps each experimental input (fixture geometry, load application point, constraint conditions, specimen dimensions) to the corresponding FEA boundary condition. CMM measurements were used to confirm dimensional agreement. No unresolved parameter mismatches were identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "FEA predictions for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement were compared against experimental means using both a percentage difference metric (<10% acceptance bound) and the validation metric E/uval (acceptance bound < 1.96). All three QoIs passed both criteria across the full 11-construct dataset. Inter-laboratory consistency was also confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must be directly traceable to the clinical and regulatory decision context for the COU.",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive qualitative assessment was conducted by the multidisciplinary credibility team to evaluate whether construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are appropriate surrogates for clinical performance in the non-cannulated pedicle screw COU. The team reviewed published biomechanical literature, FDA guidance on spinal implant testing, and internal design history files. The consensus determination is that these three QoIs collectively characterize the mechanical behavior envelope relevant to implant integrity under physiological compression-bending loading, and that each QoI maps directly to a failure mode of regulatory concern (excessive deflection, permanent deformation onset, and post-yield load-bearing capacity, respectively). The qualitative nature of this assessment reflects the inherent difficulty of mapping bench QoIs to in vivo outcomes; the team judged that the structured evidence base, while not amenable to a single numerical gradation assignment, provides sufficient confidence to support the Accepted decision in the context of a Medium model risk level and Medium decision consequence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities (ASTM F1717 bench testing of the identical construct geometry, material lot, and loading configuration as the COU) are directly relevant to the intended use. No extrapolation beyond the validated loading regime is required for the COU decision. The two-laboratory design strengthens confidence in the representativeness of the validation dataset."
    }
  ],
